{"id":"astro-ph/0701168","submitter":"Eli Waxman","authors":"E. Waxman (Weizmann Inst.)","title":"Neutrino astrophysics: A new tool for exploring the universe","comments":"Perspective article, Science Special Issue on \"particle astrophysics\"\n  (Jan 2007)","journal-ref":"Science315:63-65,2007","doi":"10.1126/science.1136638","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph hep-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  In the past four decades a new type of astronomy has emerged, where instead\nof looking up into the sky \"telescopes\" are buried miles underground or deep\nunder water or ice and search not for photons (that is, light), but rather for\nparticles called neutrinos. Neutrinos are nearly massless particles that\ninteract very weakly with matter. The detection of neutrinos emitted by the Sun\nand by a nearby supernova provided direct tests of the theory of stellar\nevolution and led to modifications of the standard model describing the\nproperties of elementary particles. At present, several very large neutrino\ndetectors are being constructed, aiming at the detection of the most powerful\nsources of energy and particles in the universe. The hope is that the detection\nof neutrinos from these sources, which are extra-Galactic and are most likely\npowered by mass accretion onto black-holes, will not only allow study of the\nsources, but, much like solar neutrinos, will also provide new information\nabout fundamental properties of matter.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 7 Jan 2007 20:47:00 GMT"}],"update_date":"2008-11-26"}
